\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: Derivatives and differences (30 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,L]$
\end_inset

, and the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\frac{d^{4}}{dx^{4}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Give 
\emph on
one
\emph default
 example of boundary conditions that make 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 self-adjoint.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we make a finite difference approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u(m\Delta x)\approx u_{m}$
\end_inset

, give a second-order accurate finite-difference approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

.
 (Hint: use a second-order accurate difference approximation four times.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: No more scalars (30 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 be some 3d region, and consider 3-component vector-valued functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 with Dirichlet boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}|_{d\Omega}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In class, we showed that the curl operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times$
\end_inset

 is then self-adjoint for the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\vec{u},\vec{v}\rangle=\int_{\Omega}\bar{\vec{u}}\cdot\vec{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 for some real-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

, where: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{A}\vec{u}=\nabla\times(c\nabla\times\vec{u})\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Under what conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 does the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\vec{u}=\frac{\partial\vec{u}}{\partial t}$
\end_inset

 have only solutions that decay exponentially to some limiting values (possibly
 nonzero)? (Hint: you should not need to do any messy integrals; the fact
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times$
\end_inset

 is self-adjoint should simplify things.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What quantities are conserved over time by solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\vec{u}=\frac{\partial\vec{u}}{\partial t}$
\end_inset

? (Hint: the nullspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\phi$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3: Guided waves (30 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the scalar wave equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}u=\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial t^{2}}$
\end_inset

 in two dimensions for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,L]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in(-\infty,\infty)$
\end_inset

, with the Neumann boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\right|_{x=0,L}=0$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a width-
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 strip extending infinitely in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 direction, with Neumann boundaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we look for separable eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,y,t)=u_{k}(x)e^{i(ky-\omega t)}$
\end_inset

, what equation and what boundary conditions does 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}$
\end_inset

 satisfy?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve your equation from the previous part to obtain the eigenfunctions
 and the dispersion relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(k)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In this geometry, it possible to propagate a wavepacket (e.g.
 a Gaussian-envelope pulse) in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 direction without it spreading out (becoming broader in time and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

)? Why or why not?
\end_layout

